<article>
    <h1>MOE train&#xAD;ing spe&#xAD;cialised teach&#xAD;ers to fa&#xAD;cil&#xAD;i&#xAD;tate reg&#xAD;u&#xAD;lar dis&#xAD;cus&#xAD;sion of con&#xAD;tem&#xAD;po&#xAD;rary is&#xAD;sues</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200725/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-25"><time>2020-07-25</time></a>
        - <span>SCIENCE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Pu&#xAD;van Ari&#xAD;arat&#xAD;nam&#xD;&#xA;Di&#xAD;rec&#xAD;tor, Char&#xAD;ac&#xAD;ter and Cit&#xAD;i&#xAD;zen&#xAD;ship Ed&#xAD;u&#xAD;ca&#xAD;tion&#xD;&#xA;Min&#xAD;istry of Ed&#xAD;u&#xAD;ca&#xAD;tion</span>
    </section>

    <p>We thank Fo­rum writ­ers Kevin Chua Hock Meng (Char­ac­ter and Cit­i­zen­ship Ed­u­ca­tion of­ten ne­glected in schools, July 23), San­taku­mari Rat­nam (Lessons on race, re­li­gion more likely to stick when taught at home, July 23) and Florence Beck­mann (Teach kids to be in­clu­sive, July 24) for their feed­back.</p>
    <p>Char­ac­ter and Cit­i­zen­ship</p>
    <p>Ed­u­ca­tion (CCE) lessons have al­ways been an in­te­gral part of our school cur­ricu­lum, and schools should de­liver these lessons con­sis­tently as part of their cur­ricu­lum and re­in­force these lessons by pro­vid­ing a range of ex­pe­ri­ences for stu­dents such as the Val­ues-in-Ac­tion pro­gramme and Learn­ing Jour­neys. It should also be de­liv­ered in part­ner­ship with par­ents.</p>
    <p>We re­view the CCE cur­ricu­lum reg­u­larly to en­sure that it re­mains rel­e­vant within the chang­ing so­cial en­vi­ron­ment, es­pe­cially with the ris­ing in­flu­ence of so­cial me­dia.</p>
    <p>In March, we an­nounced that we will be pro­gres­sively rolling out an en­hanced CCE cur­ricu­lum from next year (CCE 2021) to an­chor our stu­dents on a strong foun­da­tion of moral val­ues, good char­ac­ter and re­silience.</p>
    <p>In the CCE 2021 cur­ricu­lum, stu­dents’ CCE learn­ing ex­pe­ri­ences within and be­yond class­rooms will be more de­fined and in­ten­tional, and the to­tal ex­po­sure to CCE and op­por­tu­ni­ties for learn­ing will in­crease.</p>
    <p>For in­stance, for sec­ondary school stu­dents, teach­ers will fa­cil­i­tate reg­u­lar dis­cus­sion of con­tem­po­rary is­sues such as cy­ber bul­ly­ing, race and re­li­gion, and en­vi­ron­men­tal sus­tain­abil­ity at least once a fort­night.</p>
    <p>Equip­ping our teach­ers is key – which is why the Min­istry of Ed­u­ca­tion is now train­ing spe­cialised CCE teach­ers to lead and sup­port their col­leagues to fa­cil­i­tate these dis­cus­sions.</p>
    <p>We will also con­tinue work­ing closely with schools to re­in­force the im­por­tance of CCE and en­sure that these lessons re­main a vi­tal as­pect of each stu­dent’s school­ing ex­pe­ri­ence.</p>


</article>

